2 HOUSE BILL 1083
1 (ii) Three regular members shall be of the majority party, and two
2 regular members shall be of the principal minority party.
3 (2) (i) In Prince George’s County, the local board consists of five regular
4 members and three substitute members.
5 (ii) Four regular members and two substitute members shall be of
6 the majority party, and one regular member and one substitute member shall be of the
7 principal minority party.
8 (3) (i) In Montgomery County, the local board consists of [five] SEVEN
9 regular members [and two substitute members].
10 (ii) [Three] FOUR regular members [and one substitute member]
11 shall be of the majority party, and [two] THREE regular members [and one substitute
12 member] shall be of the principal minority party.
13 (c) Each regular member of a local board and each substitute member of a local
14 board shall:
15 (1) be appointed in accordance with subsection (g) of this section;
16 (2) be a registered voter in the county for which the individual is appointed
17 for the 5 years immediately preceding the appointment; and
18 (3) be eligible for reappointment.
19 (d) (1) The term of a member is 4 years and begins on the first Monday in June
20 of each year following a gubernatorial election.
21 (2) At the end of a term, a member continues to serve until a successor is
22 appointed and qualifies.
23 (e) Before taking office, a member shall take and subscribe to the oath prescribed
24 in Article I, § 9 of the Maryland Constitution.
25 (f) The Governor may remove a member for incompetence, misconduct, or other
26 good cause, upon written charges stating the Governor’s grounds for dismissal and after
27 affording the member notice and an ample opportunity to be heard.
28 (g) (1) The Governor shall request the county central committee representing
29 the majority party or the principal minority party, as appropriate, to submit a list of at
30 least four eligible individuals from which the Governor may make an appointment of a
31 regular member of a local board or a substitute member of the local board.
32 (2) The Governor may reject all of the nominees if the Governor determines
33 them to be unfit or incompetent, in which case the Governor shall notify the State Board in

HOUSE BILL 1083 3
1 writing and request an additional list of at least four eligible nominees from the county
2 central committee. A third list may be requested in the same manner.
3 (3) If a list containing the names of four eligible nominees is not submitted
4 within 20 days of a request or if all the nominees on three lists are rejected, the Governor
5 may appoint any eligible person who is a member of the appropriate political party.
6 (4) (i) Except as provided in subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph, each
7 appointment shall be subject to confirmation by the Senate of Maryland.
8 (ii) In Caroline, Dorchester, and Kent counties, if there is no resident
9 Senator of the particular county, the confirmation required under subparagraph (i) of this
10 paragraph shall be by the House of Delegates of Maryland.
11 (iii) If an appointee is rejected, the Governor shall make another
12 appointment from the list or lists submitted under paragraphs (1) and (2) of this subsection.
13 If a list is not provided, or the nominees on three lists are rejected, the Governor may
14 appoint an eligible individual as provided in paragraph (3) of this subsection.
15 (h) (1) Except in [Montgomery County and] Prince George’s County, if a
16 vacancy occurs on the local board, the Governor shall appoint an eligible person from the
17 same political party as the predecessor member to fill the vacancy in accordance with
18 subsection (g) of this section for the remainder of the unexpired term and until a successor
19 is appointed and qualifies.
20 (2) An appointment made while the General Assembly is not in session
21 shall be considered temporary until the appointee is confirmed by the General Assembly.
22 (i) (1) This subsection applies only in [Montgomery County and] Prince
23 George’s County.
24 (2) In the event of the absence of a regular member or a vacancy in the
25 office of a regular member, the substitute member of the same political party shall exercise
26 the powers and duties of a regular member until the regular member returns or the vacancy
27 is filled as prescribed in this subsection.
28 (3) Subject to paragraph (4) of this subsection, if a member of a local board
29 dies, resigns, is removed, or becomes ineligible:
30 (i) the substitute member belonging to the same political party shall
31 become a regular member of the local board; and
32 (ii) the Governor shall appoint an eligible person from the same
33 political party to be the new substitute member.

4 HOUSE BILL 1083
1 (4) [In Prince George’s County, if] IF a vacancy occurs on the local board
2 among the members from the majority party, the Governor shall designate one of the
3 substitute members from that party to fill the vacancy.
4 (5) If a substitute member of a local board becomes a regular member as
5 provided in paragraph (3)(i) of this subsection, dies, resigns, is removed, or becomes
6 ineligible when the confirming legislative body is not in session, the Governor shall appoint
7 an eligible person from the same political party as the predecessor substitute member to
8 fill the vacancy. That individual shall serve until the earlier of:
9 (i) the adjournment of the next session of the General Assembly; or
10 (ii) the appointment of another individual to fill the same vacancy.
11 (j) A board shall meet within 20 days after the beginning of the term to elect one
12 of its regular members as president.
13 2–202.
14 (e) In Montgomery County, the local board shall require an affirmative vote of
15 not fewer than [three] FOUR duly confirmed regular members of the local board, at least
16 one of whom shall be a member of the principal minority party, to appoint an election
17 director.
18 11–301.
19 (f) In [Montgomery County and] Prince George’s County, if a member is not
20 present at the scheduled time for vote canvassing, a substitute member of the board of
21 canvassers may be sworn in.
22 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That each substitute member of
23 the Montgomery County Board of Elections in office on the effective date of this Act shall
24 become a regular member on the effective date of this Act for the remainder of the member’s
25 term and until a successor is appointed and qualifies.
26 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
27 1, 2026.

